<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=wallster&Board=strategy&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Wallster (wallster) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 "> | </font><a href="mailto:wallster@falcon.cc.ukans.edu" OnMouseOver="window.status='Send email to Wallster.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Email</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">One thing that doesn't seem to be getting enough attention in this discussion is the concept of mana efficiency.  The two things that make kiting work are NGH(not getting hit) and mana efficiency.  The reason druids can take down reds is that they can turn a little bit of their mana into a lot of damage on the beastie.  This takes time however, so they have to use snare/sow to keep from getting squished.  Now, understanding that, you can see why bards are superior kiters.  They have infinite mana efficiency.  It doesn't matter how many hitpoints a mob has, or, more importantly, how many mobs the bard is kiting, they're going down.  Yes, the bard will take longer to take down a given mob; a LOT longer, but that time is more than made up for when considering downtime.  No need to med, probably won't have to heal.  The druid will have to med, and if they've been a bit careless, they'll have to heal and med some more.  A more pressing thing to consider is that kites seldom go perfectly.  What happens when the druid pulls a few extra mobs?  That's right, he gets his ass to the nearest zone and starts medding again, getting no xp and wasting a lot of time.  What happens to the bard when he pulls a few extra mobs?  He goes right on kiting, making them fall one-by-one, or all at once, continuing until they're all dead, or he gets bored.  What do i do when i get rooted during a kite?  I chain the root and fire up selo's again.  When a druid gets rooted....well, we won't talk about that.  What if the mob has high MR?  I can handle that too.  What happens to the druid when that DE that's been watching him kite decides it's time to kill him?(i play on T-Zek, so this is an issue for me)  The oom druid sits there and takes his beating, and with the recent change, has to med up again.  The still battle-ready bard hands the DE his ass.  When someone KS's a druid, he watches his juicy hunk of ready-made xp slip away and whines to a GM.  I turn the mob on the KSer and laugh as they die, then collect my xp.  What happens when you get lag-spiked and the mob gets in a couple shots?  I don't think i need to remind you about the disparity in AC and HP's between druids and bards.  Bards also have the ability to stationary kite, something a druid could never do.  Bards don't get interrupted.  If something goes wrong and i get knocked down to single digit HP's, i can still outrun my kite.  The druid gets run over like a mangy dog.   <p>

The worst kind of dowtime is dying; eats up a lot of time, you don't get the credit from your kill, and xp loss is a bitch.  As a bard, i have more safty valves than any other.  speed/snare/fear/mez/charm/disenchant/lull/invis/debuff/heal/teleport.  <p>

What it comes down to is that bards can kite anything a druid can(and some things they can't), with a higher degree of safety and a lesser chance of losing the kill.  Combine this with the lack of downtime, and you can see why bards are better kiters.  Bards are also more self-sufficient than druids.  I don't have to whine for a clarity so i can spend less time looking at that boring spellbook, and if something goes really wrong, i can find my own corpse.  Most importantly, when i'm done kiting, i have another option: grouping.<p>

Also, responding to Anon the necro-boy: having j-boots is a pretty big stipulation.  Hell, even a wizzie can kite with j-boots.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
