<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Hail,<br>
  I have listened to all of your kiting opinions and have observed many good points and quite a few misguided/irrelevant ones.  But I don't have the time or energy to attempt to correct them all so I will simply add my opinion which may contradict the above said points being made:<br>
  Ok, firstly, I am a Barbarian Shaman and I am referring to my experience at lvls 24 through to now 29.  I can imagine some of you maybe groaning saying what's this idiot doing arguing for himself about kiting, but I will argue my point anyway.  For one I am not saying I am the best at kiting perhaps, but I beleive I am right up there, and definately (lol) better than a bard.  My main strong point is the spell, "Malise" (resistance debuff).<br>
  I'm glad that one of you brought up mana/time efficiency.  I say mana/time because for casters, mana equals time.  It may not mean diddley squat for bards and they may be giggleing at how pathetic casters are, but I ask you how long does it take a bard to kite something?  They are saying "Yeah we have no downtime".  Hmm ok.  Their lack of downtime is definately made up by the time they TAKE to kill the damn thing.  <br>
  Ok for my next point, this big Snare thing:  Being a shaman, my DoTs definately outweigh my nukes in terms af power and efficiency, equaling less TIME spent.  The same with Druids of course.  To maximise efficiency, I use these DoTs instead of my nukes.  How can DoTs mean more time?  Instead of answering that now I will explain my Kiting strategy first:<p>

  This strategy is centered around Gnolls (lvl 25-29) in South Karana surrounding the zone to Paw.  I have been kiting these gnolls since 24 and have been leveling very nicely as a result.  At 24 they were delivering about a little less than a quarter of a bubble of experience per yellow kill, and in 3 days I gained 3 levels playing about 6hrs each day.<br>
  Ohh yeah malise's sticking power ties strongly with Charisma so I wear a crude stein and of course always have a charisma buff on (109 charisma in total now).  Also I have regen on before starting the kite and SoW.  Thats it.<br>
  The combat spells I have memmed are Envenomed breath (~250 dam in 42 seconds poison for 100 mana), root, malise (~minus 20 resistance for all except for disease), flash of light (10 mana fast-cast kind of fear spell).  Also canibleize (gives 25 mana for 50 health).<br>
Heres how it goes:<br>
  Pull with malise, run a little and cast DoT.  Let gnoll hit you first time, then cast Flash of light in between its swings (fast enough to do this).  When it starts running, root and sit.  Cannibleize in between mana ticks for most efficiency.  Because malise is on, root almost always outlasts the DoT.  When DoT runs out, reapply it and root again.  Med/Canni.  It will take 4 DoTs to kill it which means the kill takes approx 5mins all up.<br>
  You must always keep the mob still because of the DoT-movement rule.  If you dont know what that rule is, it makes it so if the Mob runs for more than 18 seconds while it has a DoT on it, the DoT only does 66% of the damage it would do if the mob was stationary.<br>
  Because of malise everything is perfect.  Root never resists and it lasts for about 50 seconds usually!  If it breaks early then it is cheap to cast anyway.  Flash of light sometimes resists but it is very fast cast and very cheap anyway.<br>
  At lvl 24 I could do this with 1 bub mana left at the end on average.  At 29 now, I end up with 3.5 bubs on average.  This means at 29 I have approx 2 minutes downtime at end of kill.  Making it 7 mins more or less a kill!<p>

  Ok back to the point I was making.  My DoTs are less time consuming because I can med/cannibleize at the same time as they are working!  By the time the DoT has finished (only 40 seconds anyway), I have gained the mana back that I used to cast it and maybe some more!  With root the DoTs are doing maximum damage as the Mob is not moving.  Thats the reason Druids cant do this as well, because of the DoT-moving rule.  Their root wont last as long and will resist heaps because they lack the resistance debuff power.<br>
  <br>
  And another point!  When Shamans get their pets, they can then Pet-DoT which is VERY easy and effective.  This involves rooting then nuking the mob heaps, then once it is off root set your pet on it &lt;WITHOUT TAUNT ON&gt;.  The pet will be nipping at its heels while you just run around watching it die.  The mob wont attack the pet because it is majorly agro on you.  When I am lvl 42, you will see me in everfrost kiting Ice giants this way and I will be LOVING it!<p>

  Yes anyway I have added my opinion, hope you dont hate it too much.  I prolly missed out heaps but I dont like concentrating too much and this has been the most I have wrote in one time since I wrote up my mail order for Everquest 8)<br>
  Goodbye all and have fun.<p>

<br>
From the 29th season Barbarian Shaman that cares,<br>
  Myrth Darkbear,<br>
  Order of xegony.<p>

PS:  Ohh yeah, Kenwiz!  How do you figure that druids are the most useful class?  Ha!  I think many would agree that shamans/enchanters are easily more useful than druids!  I know for a fact that shamans can do anything druids can and way more.  Excluding harmony, damage shield, and teleports.  The things shamans can do more than druids outweigh the importance of these three...  My 2cp.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
